== Data Model ==

The pipeline produces a richly structured result. Every entity in the output is typed, linked, and inspectable.

{{mermaid}}

erDiagram
    INPUT_ARTICLE ||--o{ ATOMIC_CLAIM : "extracts"
    ATOMIC_CLAIM ||--o{ SEARCH_QUERY : "generates"
    SEARCH_QUERY }o--o{ SOURCE : "discovers"
    SOURCE ||--o{ EVIDENCE_ITEM : "yields"
    EVIDENCE_ITEM |o--o| EVIDENCE_SCOPE : "has"
    EVIDENCE_SCOPE }o--|| CLAIM_ASSESSMENT_BOUNDARY : "clusters into"
    EVIDENCE_ITEM }o--|| CLAIM_ASSESSMENT_BOUNDARY : "assigned to"
    ATOMIC_CLAIM ||--o{ CB_CLAIM_VERDICT : "receives"
    CB_CLAIM_VERDICT }o--o{ EVIDENCE_ITEM : "cites"
    CB_CLAIM_VERDICT }o--o| CLAIM_ASSESSMENT_BOUNDARY : "scoped by"
    CB_CLAIM_VERDICT }o--|| OVERALL_ASSESSMENT : "aggregates into"
    OVERALL_ASSESSMENT ||--o{ CLAIM_ASSESSMENT_BOUNDARY : "presents"
    CB_CLAIM_VERDICT ||--o{ BOUNDARY_FINDING : "contains"
    BOUNDARY_FINDING }o--|| CLAIM_ASSESSMENT_BOUNDARY : "per boundary"

    INPUT_ARTICLE {
        string id_PK
        string inputType "text or url"
        string detectedInputType "claim or article"
        string impliedClaim "LLM-extracted thesis"
        string riskTier "A B or C"
    }

    ATOMIC_CLAIM {
        string id_PK "AC_01 AC_02"
        string statement "The verifiable assertion"
        string category "factual evaluative procedural"
        string centrality "high medium"
        string harmPotential "critical high medium low"
        string claimDirection "supports_thesis contradicts_thesis contextual"
        float specificityScore "0-1 Gate1 min 0.6"
        json keyEntities "Named entities referenced"
    }

    SOURCE {
        string id_PK
        string url
        string title
        float trackRecordScore "0.0-1.0"
        float trackRecordConfidence "0.0-1.0"
        string category
    }

    EVIDENCE_ITEM {
        string id_PK "EV_001 EV_002"
        string statement "Extracted evidence text"
        string category "statistic expert_quote event etc"
        string claimDirection "supports contradicts neutral"
        string probativeValue "high medium low"
        string sourceType "peer_reviewed_study news_primary etc"
        boolean isDerivative "Cites another source study"
    }

    EVIDENCE_SCOPE {
        string name "Short label"
        string methodology "ISO 14040 EU RED II etc"
        string temporal "Source data time period"
        string geographic "Source data geography"
    }

    CLAIM_ASSESSMENT_BOUNDARY {
        string id_PK "CB_01 CB_02"
        string name "Human-readable label"
        string description "What this boundary represents"
        string methodology "Dominant methodology"
        float internalCoherence "0-1 consistency"
        int evidenceCount
    }

    CB_CLAIM_VERDICT {
        string id_PK
        float truthPercentage "0-100"
        string verdict "7-point scale label"
        float confidence "0-100"
        string reasoning "LLM-generated explanation"
        boolean isContested
        json supportingEvidenceIds_FK
        json contradictingEvidenceIds_FK
    }

    BOUNDARY_FINDING {
        string boundaryId_FK
        float truthPercentage "Per-boundary 0-100"
        float confidence "Per-boundary 0-100"
        string evidenceDirection "supports contradicts mixed"
    }

    OVERALL_ASSESSMENT {
        float truthPercentage "0-100 weighted"
        string verdict "7-point scale label"
        float confidence "0-100 weighted"
        json verdictNarrative "headline keyFinding limitations"
        json coverageMatrix "claims x boundaries"
        json qualityGates "gate1Stats gate4Stats"
    }

{{/mermaid}}

(% class="box infomessage" %)
(((
**Key insight:** A claim can have different truth values in different ClaimAssessmentBoundaries (e.g., a study may be "Mostly True" under one methodology but "Leaning False" under another). The data model captures this nuance via BoundaryFindings, not just a single verdict.
)))

=== Why This Matters Beyond RAG ===

Classic RAG improves access to external memory, but it does not by itself define how retrieved evidence should be decomposed, compared, validated, and audited. The original RAG paper already frames provenance as an open problem. Schimanski et al.'s ACL 2024 paper sharpens this further: evidence-based QA often fails on **source quality** and **answer attributability**. DIRAS (NAACL 2025) then shows that even //relevance// needs nuanced definitions and calibrated scores beyond shallow semantic matching.

FactHarbor's answer is a typed intermediate representation that constrains what retrieval can mean downstream:

|=RAG Challenge|=FactHarbor Data-Model Guardrail
|Retrieved passages may mix incompatible methodologies, time windows, or jurisdictions|**EvidenceScope** records methodology, temporal, geographic, source-type, and analytical-dimension metadata on each EvidenceItem
|A single prompt may blur multiple assertions into one answer|**AtomicClaims** force explicit claim decomposition before verdicting
|Retrieved evidence may be compared apples-to-oranges|**ClaimAssessmentBoundary** clusters only compatible EvidenceScopes into separate analytical frames
|Missing coverage is easy to hide inside a fluent answer|**CoverageMatrix** records claims x boundaries evidence distribution explicitly for verdicting, aggregation, and auditability
|Weak or unstable outputs can be hidden by narrative fluency|**QualityGates**, **confidence tiers**, and **analysisWarnings** surface low-confidence or degraded runs as first-class output
|Runs are hard to reproduce once prompts/configs change|**Schema versioning** plus **per-job config snapshots** preserve the exact analytical setup used for a result

This is why the data model is central to the research platform claim. Retrieval happens in Stage 2, but the main scientific object is the structured analysis graph built around it: AtomicClaims, EvidenceItems, EvidenceScopes, ClaimAssessmentBoundaries, Verdicts, QualityGates, and supporting analytical artifacts such as the CoverageMatrix.

