(((
**Research opportunity:** The federation layer raises open questions in distributed fact-checking: how to reconcile conflicting verdicts across instances, detect cross-instance contradictions, and maintain quality guarantees in a decentralized network.
)))

----

== Goals for First Public Release (V1.0) ==

The pipeline works end-to-end today. To move from working prototype to a public service people can rely on, five engineering goals must be met:

|=Goal|=Current State|=V1.0 Target|=Why It Matters
|**Scalability**|Single host, 3 concurrent jobs|Horizontal scaling, PostgreSQL, queue-based job dispatch|A public service must handle hundreds of concurrent users without degradation
|**Performance**|~3-5 min per single-claim analysis|< 90 seconds for single claims; parallel stage execution|Users will not wait 5 minutes — response time directly affects adoption
|**Stability**|Operational but manual recovery; circuit breakers for provider failures|Auto-recovery, health monitoring (Prometheus + Grafana), graceful degradation|A public service must run unattended 24/7 without manual intervention
|**Repeatability**|Same claim can produce different verdicts across runs (LLM stochasticity, live web evidence)|Verdict stability within defined tolerance bands; self-consistency gating; evidence caching|Trust requires that the same claim analysed twice yields substantially the same verdict — users and researchers must be able to reproduce results
|**Cost Reduction**|~$0.15-0.25 per analysis (model tiering already saves 50-70%)|< $0.05 per analysis through aggressive caching, smaller models where sufficient, evidence reuse|At scale, every analysis costs real money — a non-profit must minimize per-analysis cost to remain sustainable

(% class="box infomessage" %)
(((
**Research angle:** Repeatability and cost reduction are open research questions. How do you achieve stable verdicts when evidence changes daily and LLM outputs are stochastic? How do you reduce model costs without degrading analytical quality?
)))

