== Vision Beyond V1.0 ==

After the first public release, FactHarbor's roadmap includes features driven by user demand and research opportunities:

=== Platform & Integration Architecture ===

The analysis engine is designed as a **headless service** — the pipeline and Public API are the core, with multiple UI integration paths built on top:

|=Integration|=Target|=Description
|**Public REST API**|V1.0|The foundation — programmatic access for any client. Journalists, researchers, and third-party apps consume verdicts, evidence, and metadata via API
|**Web Application**|Current|The primary UI — submit claims, browse analyses, explore evidence landscapes
|**Browser Extensions**|V1.1+|Chrome, Firefox, Safari — right-click any text on any website to fact-check it instantly
|**Mobile Apps (iOS/Android)**|V1.5+|Native apps with push notifications for tracked claims; on-the-go verification
|**Embeddable Widgets**|V1.1+|JavaScript widgets for publishers to embed live verdicts directly in their articles
|**CMS Plugins**|V1.5+|WordPress, Drupal — direct integration into content management workflows
|**ClaimReview Schema.org**|V1.1+|Structured data so verdicts appear as Google rich snippets in search results

=== Advanced Analysis ===

|=Feature|=Target|=Why
|**Image & Video Verification**|V1.5+|Reverse image search, EXIF metadata, deepfake detection
|**Semantic Search (Vector DB)**|V2.0+|Find related claims across the full corpus
|**Contradiction Network**|V2.0+|Global detection of contradictory claims across analyses
|**Evidence Reuse & Caching**|V1.1+|Previously gathered evidence accelerates new analyses on related claims

=== Community & Collaboration ===

|=Feature|=Target|=Why
|**Public Comment Threads**|V2.0+|Community discussion on individual verdicts
|**Expert Review Workflow**|V1.5+|Domain experts consulted for high-stakes or contested claims
|**Collaborative Annotation**|V2.0+|Users annotate and discuss evidence together
|**Team Workspaces**|V1.5+|Shared environments for newsroom or research group fact-checking

=== Federation (V2.0+) ===

|=Feature|=Target|=Why
|**Claim Synchronization**|V2.0+|Independent instances share verified claims across organizations
|**Distributed Verdict Consensus**|V2.0+|Cross-node validation while maintaining source attribution
|**Data Sovereignty per Node**|V2.0+|GDPR compliance per region; each node maintains autonomy
|**Cross-Node Contradiction Detection**|V2.0+|Identify conflicting verdicts across the federation

=== Source Reliability as a Standalone Service ===

The Source Reliability (SR) module — which evaluates domain credibility using multi-provider LLM assessment — is designed for **extraction as an independent service**. It already has its own database, cache isolation, and UCM configuration. As a standalone API, it could serve:

* **Other fact-checking platforms** — any system that needs domain credibility scores
* **Newsrooms** — evaluate source trustworthiness before citing
* **Researchers** — systematic, reproducible media source assessment at scale
* **Browser extensions** — real-time credibility indicators while browsing

=== Accessibility & Internationalization ===

|=Feature|=Target|=Why
|**WCAG 2.1 AA Compliance**|Beta+|Screen readers, keyboard navigation, high-contrast modes
|**Multilingual UI (10+ languages)**|V1.0+|Interface beyond English — matching the multilingual analysis capability
|**RTL Language Support**|V1.5+|Arabic, Hebrew, and other right-to-left languages

