== Why Collaborate: Mutual Benefits ==

A collaboration between FactHarbor and UZH is not one-directional — both sides bring what the other needs.

(% class="box infomessage" %)
(((
**Public research references behind this section:** Schimanski et al., ACL 2024 (//Towards Faithful and Robust LLM Specialists for Evidence-Based Question-Answering//); Ni et al., NAACL 2025 (//DIRAS: Efficient LLM Annotation of Document Relevance for Retrieval Augmented Generation//); Tobias Schimanski ACL Anthology author page; Markus Leippold's UZH profile; Elliott Ash's ETH profile.
)))

=== What FactHarbor Gains ===

|=Benefit|=Why It Matters
|**Rigorous evaluation methodology**|Tobias brings published metrics for source attribution (ACL 2024) and relevance scoring (DIRAS) — FactHarbor currently evaluates quality informally. Formal benchmarks make the system credible to the academic community.
|**Research framing**|A UZH partnership would help turn internal quality checks into publishable evaluation questions, benchmark protocols, and ablation studies.
|**Access to research infrastructure**|Potential access to university compute, datasets, and a broader UZH / ETH-adjacent NLP research network, depending on project structure and collaborators.
|**Grant vehicle**|Innosuisse or BRIDGE could provide a credible structure for funding research effort around the platform, subject to institutional fit, eligibility, and proposal design.
|**Publication pipeline**|Joint papers at top venues (ACL, EMNLP, NAACL) create visibility and attract contributors.
|**Student contributors**|Bachelor/Master thesis projects on specific pipeline components become realistic once the collaboration matures.

=== What Tobias / UZH Could Gain ===

|=Benefit|=Why It Matters
|**A deployed, operational system**|Unlike most research prototypes, FactHarbor runs end-to-end on real claims today. Research can happen on a live system producing real artifacts, not only synthetic benchmarks.
|**Modular research testbed**|An end-to-end multi-agent debate system with live evidence retrieval — few equivalent systems exist in production. Each pipeline stage produces inspectable intermediate artifacts, and all analysis parameters are configurable via UCM with per-job config snapshots for reproducibility.
|**Domain-agnostic scope**|Tobias' public publication record includes climate / sustainability retrieval work and evidence-based QA. FactHarbor would let similar evaluation ideas be tested in a broader, general-domain fact-checking setting.
|**Publishable open problems**|Report stability, evidence quality metrics, cross-provider debate dynamics, and source reliability benchmarking are all concrete topics that could support papers, with system data already being generated.
|**Industry partnership for grants**|For industry-linked funding schemes, FactHarbor can serve as a concrete implementation partner and real-world validation environment if the project is scoped jointly.
|**Open-source visibility**|Contributions to an open-source, non-profit project are visible, citable, and reusable by the community — not locked behind a corporate NDA.

(% class="box warningmessage" %)
(((
**The key asymmetry:** FactHarbor has a working system that still lacks formal evaluation. Tobias' published work brings evaluation methodology that could be stress-tested on a live, production-scale testbed. Together, that is a strong research fit.
)))

----

== Research Overlap ==

=== Source Attribution (your ACL 2024 work) ===

Your ACL 2024 //Faithful LLM Specialists// paper formalizes the citation fidelity problem: LLMs cite wrong sources or misrepresent what sources say. FactHarbor addresses this structurally: every verdict traces to specific evidence items with source reliability scores. A post-verdict **grounding check** (Step 5: Validator) exists but currently runs in advisory mode — it flags mismatches without blocking publication. Formalizing and enforcing attribution quality is an open problem where that evaluation framework could directly improve the pipeline.

=== Evidence Quality Scoring (DIRAS, NAACL 2025) ===

Our evidence filter assigns //probativeValue// (high/medium/low) via LLM prompt — a categorical approach. DIRAS shows that explicit relevance definitions per query and continuous calibrated scores significantly improve scoring. Integrating DIRAS-style relevance assessment could strengthen our evidence weighting in verdict aggregation.

=== Multi-Agent Debate (Climinator parallel) ===

FactHarbor's 5-step debate is adjacent to, but not the same as, the mediator-advocate line explored in climate fact-checking systems such as Climinator. FactHarbor adds self-consistency checking, cross-provider diversity, and evidence-weighted contestation rules. Unlike domain-specific systems, this architecture is **topic-agnostic** — it works for climate, politics, health, economics, or other domains without modification.

=== Collaboration Opportunities ===

* **Evidence quality metrics** — formalize and benchmark our filtering with your evaluation methodology
* **Retrieval evaluation** — measure how well our iterative search captures relevant evidence
* **Source credibility benchmarking** — evaluate our multi-provider reliability scoring
* **Multi-agent debate architecture** — study and improve the debate pattern itself

