== Demo Walkthrough Guide ==

=== 1. User Experience: Submit & Explore ===

|=Step|=What to Show|=What to Say
|**Submit a claim**|Navigate to ##/analyze##, enter a claim (let Tobias choose one), click Analyze|"You can submit any claim in any language. The system accepts free text or URLs."
|**Job progress**|Show the job status page — stages progressing in real-time|"You can see each pipeline stage as it executes: extraction, research, clustering, debate, aggregation."
|**Verdict overview**|Show the overall verdict badge, truth percentage, confidence tier|"The verdict is not binary — it shows a 7-point scale with a confidence level. Here we got [verdict] with [confidence] confidence."
|**Per-claim verdicts**|Expand individual AtomicClaim verdicts|"The system decomposed your input into [N] verifiable claims. Each has its own verdict with cited evidence."
|**Boundary findings**|Show per-boundary breakdown for a claim|"This claim has different truth values depending on the analytical boundary — [example: methodology X says mostly true, methodology Y says mixed]."
|**Evidence trail**|Click through to supporting/contradicting evidence items|"Every verdict traces back to specific evidence. You can see the source URL, the extracted statement, its probative value, and the source reliability score."
|**Quality gates panel**|Show Gate 1 and Gate 4 results|"Two mandatory quality gates — Gate 1 filtered out [N] weak claims, Gate 4 assessed confidence calibration."

=== 2. Admin: Configuration & Control ===

|=Step|=What to Show|=What to Say
|**Admin dashboard**|Navigate to ##/admin## — show the config overview|"Everything that affects analysis behavior is configurable at runtime — no code changes needed."
|**Pipeline config**|Open pipeline settings — show model selection, debate roles, temperatures|"You can see which models are assigned to which pipeline stage, and the debate role configuration: Anthropic for advocate, OpenAI for challenger."
|**Search config**|Show search provider settings, iteration limits, budget controls|"Research intensity is tunable — max iterations, providers, evidence sufficiency thresholds."
|**Calculation config**|Show aggregation weights, triangulation thresholds, harm potential multipliers|"These parameters control how evidence is weighted, how cross-boundary agreement affects confidence, and how harmful claims get extra scrutiny."
|**Config comparison**|Show the diff view: current vs. defaults|"The admin can compare running config against defaults to see what has been tuned — full audit trail."
|**Job history**|Navigate to ##/jobs## — show list of completed analyses with verdicts|"Every analysis is stored with its full config snapshot, so any result can be reproduced with the exact settings used."

=== 3. Source Reliability Database ===

|=Step|=What to Show|=What to Say
|**SR overview**|Navigate to ##/admin/source-reliability## (or show the SR cache DB)|"Source reliability is a separate subsystem with its own database and evaluation pipeline."
|**Domain lookup**|Search for a well-known domain (e.g., reuters.com, wikipedia.org)|"Each domain gets a credibility score from 0.0 to 1.0, evaluated by multiple LLM providers with cross-check refinement."
|**Score breakdown**|Show trackRecordScore, trackRecordConfidence, consensus flag|"The score includes a confidence level — a domain with 2 evaluations has lower confidence than one with 5. Consensus means all evaluators agreed."
|**Source types**|Show different source type classifications|"Sources are classified by type — peer-reviewed study, government report, news primary, opinion, collaborative reference (Wikipedia). Each type carries different weight in the analysis."
|**Impact on verdict**|Reference back to the analysis report — show how SR scores affected evidence weighting|"In the report we just saw, this source had a reliability score of [X], which influenced how much weight its evidence carried in the verdict."

